WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:15.080
So, picture this, it was a beautiful Tuesday morning in 2018, I've just wrapped up the

00:00:15.080 --> 00:00:20.840
final test of a Shiny app, which I'm convinced to be the game changer our team needs.

00:00:20.840 --> 00:00:23.799
My coffee even tastes like success.

00:00:24.280 --> 00:00:32.520
Reality check, fast forward a month, the app I thought was gold had zero visits.

00:00:32.520 --> 00:00:36.560
Now I was no rookie in Shiny after Elephant back then, I've already built and launched

00:00:36.560 --> 00:00:42.139
half a dozen of those, but here's the twist, the popularity did not grow as I added more

00:00:42.139 --> 00:00:44.959
fancy widgets and functions.

00:00:44.959 --> 00:00:52.000
One day, while watching Silicon Valley, a TV show about the ups and downs of a startup,

00:00:52.000 --> 00:01:00.320
it hit me, that building and launching a Shiny app is just like starting a company, where

00:01:00.320 --> 00:01:04.040
the app is the product.

00:01:04.040 --> 00:01:07.559
It is important, but also just one piece of the whole puzzle.

00:01:07.559 --> 00:01:10.260
There are other things to consider in the whole process.

00:01:10.260 --> 00:01:14.639
In the next 16 minutes, I will walk through all the other similarities between the two,

00:01:14.639 --> 00:01:22.440
and trace back a mind map that helped turn my apps from zero usage to now handling 160,000

00:01:22.440 --> 00:01:25.519
requests in the last few years.

00:01:25.519 --> 00:01:31.599
Now similar to a startup, a Shiny app also starts from idea.

00:01:31.599 --> 00:01:36.320
So in the startup world, there's a saying, there's a quote about why do you start a company

00:01:36.320 --> 00:01:42.080
that goes, don't build a startup for the sake of building a startup.

00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:47.559
Trying to get people more focused on the problem it tries to solve, which can be perfectly

00:01:47.559 --> 00:01:50.040
applied to Shiny apps.

00:01:50.040 --> 00:01:54.199
To build a Shiny app, we need to first find out the problem.

00:01:54.199 --> 00:01:58.519
Well this is probably easy to say, but for me, I came up with absolutely nothing for

00:01:58.519 --> 00:02:00.660
the first few months after learning about Shiny.

00:02:00.660 --> 00:02:03.599
So where can we look for these ideas?

00:02:03.599 --> 00:02:05.599
Here are the directions I found.

00:02:05.599 --> 00:02:07.680
Now think about all of these startups.

00:02:07.680 --> 00:02:11.240
Many of those ideas would fall under the following three categories.

00:02:11.240 --> 00:02:13.720
Things that everyone can use.

00:02:13.720 --> 00:02:16.800
Things that would replace repeated work processes.

00:02:16.800 --> 00:02:20.399
And things that would solve challenges in a few organizations or industries.

00:02:20.399 --> 00:02:25.240
But now even with these directions, they're still hard to come up with.

00:02:25.240 --> 00:02:29.839
But luckily we are trying to implement a Shiny app at a workplace, which allows us to add

00:02:29.839 --> 00:02:32.199
one condition in the end.

00:02:32.199 --> 00:02:38.800
Now for Shiny apps, looking for things that everyone can use in the company is less difficult.

00:02:38.800 --> 00:02:45.440
And repeated work processes in a department are probably common to spot.

00:02:45.440 --> 00:02:50.399
And pain points for a specific team are much easier to identify.

00:02:50.399 --> 00:02:54.880
Now these directions may provide you a more targeted view when you are trying to find

00:02:54.880 --> 00:02:56.979
the problem.

00:02:56.979 --> 00:03:01.240
Now once you find the initial idea, it does not mean just go ahead and do it.

00:03:01.240 --> 00:03:04.199
We still need to validate them.

00:03:04.199 --> 00:03:08.759
So for startups, they would do market research to try to measure the need and talk to consumers.

00:03:09.520 --> 00:03:10.520
To understand the problem.

00:03:10.520 --> 00:03:14.960
If they don't do that, I'm pretty sure we would all have a glow-in-the-dark sunglasses

00:03:14.960 --> 00:03:15.960
now.

00:03:15.960 --> 00:03:20.479
So for Shiny apps, to make sure there is a real need, we can do our own market research

00:03:20.479 --> 00:03:25.360
by, for example, measuring the amount of efforts the Shiny app could save to try to quantify

00:03:25.360 --> 00:03:26.839
the impact.

00:03:26.839 --> 00:03:31.759
And we can also talk to the potential users, in this case, our colleagues, to understand

00:03:31.759 --> 00:03:36.160
the problem and how may the new solution affect their workflow.

00:03:37.160 --> 00:03:41.320
Now if after a while, there is still no idea that comes to mind, we can still see what

00:03:41.320 --> 00:03:43.520
are the ideas we can copy.

00:03:43.520 --> 00:03:46.740
After all, not all startups were built on over-agent ideas.

00:03:46.740 --> 00:03:51.399
To save myself from unnecessary lawsuits, I'm not going to name any names, but it is

00:03:51.399 --> 00:03:56.399
totally fine to learn from cases that work for other companies and organizations and

00:03:56.399 --> 00:03:57.679
apply it to yours.

00:03:57.679 --> 00:04:02.960
So with that, I've listed a few examples on my blog, which I'm going to share in the end,

00:04:02.960 --> 00:04:06.880
that may help you customize a solution for your organization.

00:04:06.880 --> 00:04:11.639
To dive deeper in just one example, oftentimes when stakeholders want to make, let's just

00:04:11.639 --> 00:04:16.600
say, data-informed decisions, they would reach out to the data teams, who then runs a set

00:04:16.600 --> 00:04:23.119
of SQL code to extract from databases, compile the results, and share it back with the stakeholders.

00:04:23.119 --> 00:04:28.959
Now when those SQL codes are similar or easy to modify, it is possible for us to save some

00:04:28.959 --> 00:04:29.959
efforts.

00:04:29.959 --> 00:04:33.480
To do that, we can create a Shiny app that allows stakeholders to directly interact with

00:04:33.480 --> 00:04:37.000
the databases without having to go through the data teams.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:42.000
We can even make it possible to email the results so that nobody has to wait for the

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:47.720
job to complete, and make it possible to handle multiple requests at the same time.

00:04:47.720 --> 00:04:53.040
So overall, to find the ideas for both startups and Shiny apps, there are three directions

00:04:53.040 --> 00:04:58.399
we can think about, but we have a much smaller scope for Shiny apps.

00:04:58.399 --> 00:05:02.720
And before any development work, we need to validate the idea by possibly quantify

00:05:02.720 --> 00:05:05.200
the impact and talk to the users.

00:05:05.200 --> 00:05:11.359
Lastly, if there's no idea that comes to mind, we can see what are the ideas we can copy.

00:05:11.359 --> 00:05:17.519
And now, after confirming the idea, startups will need financial support.

00:05:17.519 --> 00:05:19.160
So will your Shiny apps.

00:05:19.160 --> 00:05:22.880
So in that, in pitching for investments, there is another saying in the startup world that

00:05:22.880 --> 00:05:27.160
goes, don't pitch the product, pitch the business.

00:05:27.160 --> 00:05:31.399
We need to get people focused on pitching the broader business opportunities, which

00:05:31.399 --> 00:05:36.320
can also apply to Shiny apps.

00:05:36.320 --> 00:05:43.119
And when asking resources for Shiny app development, we need to focus less on the Shiny app features

00:05:43.119 --> 00:05:44.839
and more on the impact.

00:05:44.839 --> 00:05:48.799
And you may already have the impact while doing the stage of validating your ideas.

00:05:48.799 --> 00:05:52.200
So we just need to find the right group of people to talk to.

00:05:52.200 --> 00:05:54.559
So for startups, there are a few.

00:05:54.559 --> 00:05:56.559
The first one is the incubators.

00:05:56.559 --> 00:06:01.959
So this is where the incubator founder, who is more experienced, more resourceful, will

00:06:01.959 --> 00:06:04.320
guide you as you build your product.

00:06:04.320 --> 00:06:09.440
And more often, they will work together with you as with the investors when more investments

00:06:09.440 --> 00:06:10.839
are needed.

00:06:10.839 --> 00:06:15.320
This could be a common case for Shiny apps where you are still you.

00:06:15.320 --> 00:06:19.920
The incubator founder in this case would be your manager, who would provide you the initial

00:06:19.920 --> 00:06:22.239
investments of time and resources.

00:06:22.239 --> 00:06:25.839
And instead of presenting together with the investors, you guys would present together

00:06:25.839 --> 00:06:30.320
with the stakeholders when more investments are needed.

00:06:30.320 --> 00:06:35.320
Now for startups that do not work with incubators but still need investments, you will sometimes

00:06:35.320 --> 00:06:41.440
see them on pitch contests like Shark Tank, where they are directly pitching in front

00:06:41.440 --> 00:06:44.160
of the investors.

00:06:44.160 --> 00:06:50.200
For us, the idea is to look for internal opportunities like hackathon or innovation activities where

00:06:50.200 --> 00:06:54.720
you can directly bring your ideas forward in front of the stakeholders.

00:06:54.720 --> 00:07:02.119
Now even if the previous two are not an option, you can still try the last option to get the

00:07:02.119 --> 00:07:08.600
funding via crowdfunding option like Kickstarter, where you are directly pitching from the users.

00:07:08.600 --> 00:07:12.720
Similarly for Shiny apps, we can do the same by directly connecting with the users, in

00:07:12.720 --> 00:07:17.399
this case your colleagues, to get them to promote your app and ask for the resources

00:07:17.399 --> 00:07:19.480
from their supervisor.

00:07:19.480 --> 00:07:22.839
One person may not provide enough help, multiple might.

00:07:22.839 --> 00:07:25.279
You get the idea.

00:07:25.279 --> 00:07:29.679
Now overall, to find the investments, while startups would work with incubators, we would

00:07:29.679 --> 00:07:33.359
work with our supervisors to get the initial investments.

00:07:33.359 --> 00:07:38.200
And when startups would get on pitch contests like Shark Tank, we can look for internal

00:07:38.200 --> 00:07:43.279
opportunities like hackathon or innovation activities to bring your ideas forward in

00:07:43.279 --> 00:07:44.920
front of the stakeholders.

00:07:44.920 --> 00:07:49.519
Lastly, even if the previous two are not an option, you can still try the crowdfunding

00:07:49.519 --> 00:07:55.359
option like Kickstarter to directly pitch resources from the users.

00:07:55.359 --> 00:08:00.519
Now once your investments are secured, time to develop product.

00:08:00.519 --> 00:08:05.720
Now when it comes to Shiny app development, there are so many great resources, I'm going

00:08:05.720 --> 00:08:07.959
to keep this one very brief.

00:08:07.959 --> 00:08:12.880
But when it comes to developing the product, there is another quote in the startup world

00:08:12.880 --> 00:08:18.200
that goes, it is not about building the best product, but building the right one.

00:08:18.200 --> 00:08:22.239
Trying to get people focused on just the necessary features.

00:08:22.239 --> 00:08:27.119
And which also applies to the Shiny app, because the one thing that both startups and Shiny

00:08:27.119 --> 00:08:31.640
apps need to steer away from is to be overdeveloped.

00:08:31.640 --> 00:08:37.280
To do that, while startups would try to stick with the core features, for Shiny apps, we

00:08:37.280 --> 00:08:42.919
need to minimize all the nice-to-have widgets, which can be really hard to do.

00:08:42.919 --> 00:08:47.280
Because I know for me, and also for some of the other Shiny app developers, coming up

00:08:47.280 --> 00:08:52.320
with the possible features to add to the app, it's almost like knee-jerk reaction.

00:08:52.320 --> 00:08:53.320
You just can't help it.

00:08:53.320 --> 00:08:58.280
For example, when there is state or province data, I would immediately think about possibly

00:08:58.280 --> 00:09:01.760
adding an interactive core of the platform.

00:09:01.760 --> 00:09:07.919
And when there is a plain text file export needed, I instantly think about possibly adding

00:09:07.919 --> 00:09:12.159
a download button, which will allow users to download the HTML document that would host

00:09:12.159 --> 00:09:18.200
the plots and tables, which often ended with functionality that wasn't utilized, as well

00:09:18.200 --> 00:09:21.760
as overwhelmed users.

00:09:21.760 --> 00:09:26.000
And now, even if we can keep ourselves in check, it is still possible that new ideas

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:29.039
may come up throughout the development.

00:09:29.039 --> 00:09:37.679
Now, for startups, while they will need to avoid scope from all areas, for Shiny apps,

00:09:37.679 --> 00:09:42.320
we will need to manage all the new feature requests coming from users or stakeholders.

00:09:42.320 --> 00:09:48.919
Now, oftentimes, it is going to be more than just the amount of efforts it takes to make

00:09:48.919 --> 00:09:53.880
the feature possible, but whether if it is a necessary one.

00:09:53.880 --> 00:10:00.919
Because almost no one would mind waiting for a few extra days to get a Swiss army knife

00:10:00.919 --> 00:10:03.760
when all they needed is a toothpick.

00:10:04.440 --> 00:10:08.159
Now, after the product is built or the Shiny app is built, time to take off the Shiny app

00:10:08.159 --> 00:10:12.679
you all have had and try to focus on getting users.

00:10:12.679 --> 00:10:16.119
After all, you can't expect the users to come to you automatically.

00:10:16.119 --> 00:10:22.400
As another saying also in the startup world goes, build it and they will come, only happens

00:10:22.400 --> 00:10:23.799
in the movies.

00:10:23.799 --> 00:10:27.799
So what are the things that startups would try to do to get more customers?

00:10:27.799 --> 00:10:32.119
Well, for that, I would probably need to take the whole rest of the afternoon to talk about

00:10:32.119 --> 00:10:34.039
it, but luckily, I don't have the slides.

00:10:34.039 --> 00:10:37.039
So let me just mention a few examples there.

00:10:37.039 --> 00:10:42.640
One of the first things the startup would try to do is to market the product by bringing

00:10:42.640 --> 00:10:48.479
a strong brand identity, which is something that we can do as well for the Shiny app development,

00:10:48.479 --> 00:10:51.200
to try to bring our own personality.

00:10:51.200 --> 00:10:56.159
For example, you may know some of these as the 80s action movies, but what you do not

00:10:56.159 --> 00:11:02.000
know is that they are also the names of the app that I built and launched at work.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:05.840
For the record, these Shiny app functionalities have nothing to do with the movie content,

00:11:05.840 --> 00:11:11.320
but the truth is that no one is going to remember the app name if I try to name it solely based

00:11:11.320 --> 00:11:13.479
on what it really does.

00:11:13.479 --> 00:11:17.359
But combined with my personal interest and the weak connection I can find between the

00:11:17.359 --> 00:11:23.640
business goals as well as the app name, I was able to create a fun and a popular reference

00:11:23.640 --> 00:11:25.320
among users.

00:11:25.320 --> 00:11:31.200
And these are the apps that helped solve 160,000 requests in the last few years.

00:11:31.200 --> 00:11:35.479
The other thing that startups would try to do is to try to make their product more accessible

00:11:35.479 --> 00:11:39.479
via, let's just say, enhancing the search engine results.

00:11:39.479 --> 00:11:44.320
Luckily, we don't have to do that for an internal Shiny app, but we can certainly try to make

00:11:44.320 --> 00:11:49.679
things more accessible by building a landing page with CNAME.

00:11:49.679 --> 00:11:55.039
So imagine these are the list of Shinies that you have at your workplace, along with assimilated

00:11:55.039 --> 00:11:56.039
links.

00:11:56.359 --> 00:12:02.159
Now, if your users are not super organized with web links or a super user bookmarking,

00:12:02.159 --> 00:12:06.359
it is almost a certainty that someone will need to dig around the communication will

00:12:06.359 --> 00:12:10.679
ask you about the links of their Shiny app or the Shiny app that you built.

00:12:10.679 --> 00:12:16.679
So instead of asking my users to do that, I've set up a CNAME, which in this case is

00:12:16.679 --> 00:12:22.320
an alias to an internal web address, and built a landing page that would host the directory

00:12:22.320 --> 00:12:24.840
for all the Shiny apps that I built.

00:12:24.840 --> 00:12:30.719
Now, for the users, instead of having to remember all of these links above, all they

00:12:30.719 --> 00:12:34.880
need to remember now is one word, the CNAME.

00:12:34.880 --> 00:12:41.239
Put it into the internal web browser, which will take them to the landing page that will

00:12:41.239 --> 00:12:43.239
host all of these applications.

00:12:43.239 --> 00:12:47.559
And based on the previous movie reference I had, you can probably guess what that CNAME

00:12:47.559 --> 00:12:50.080
might be for my landing page.

00:12:50.119 --> 00:12:55.400
Now, the last thing the start-ups would want to do is to enable the product content sharing

00:12:55.400 --> 00:12:57.640
via what it does.

00:12:57.640 --> 00:13:03.119
For Shiny apps, we can achieve similar effects by allowing the users to share the following

00:13:03.119 --> 00:13:04.119
things.

00:13:04.119 --> 00:13:06.440
For example, the work results.

00:13:06.440 --> 00:13:11.080
And this is where we can easily enable by having an email-only option or download button

00:13:11.080 --> 00:13:14.679
of the results from the Shiny app.

00:13:14.679 --> 00:13:18.599
Work progress can also be shared if we have a built-in functionality for the users to

00:13:18.599 --> 00:13:24.359
see the sessions that they have ever used and what are the before and after impact.

00:13:24.359 --> 00:13:28.840
And lastly, no one has ever said that Shiny apps couldn't be fun.

00:13:28.840 --> 00:13:33.760
We have created customized messages that will pop up randomly while a user is waiting for

00:13:33.760 --> 00:13:34.760
a job to complete.

00:13:34.760 --> 00:13:40.760
Now, for the record, Phyllis is a real co-worker and a user of the app.

00:13:40.760 --> 00:13:47.559
Now, overall, to reach more customers, while start-ups would market the product via a strong

00:13:47.559 --> 00:13:53.159
brand identity, we can do the same by bringing our own personality starting with a name.

00:13:53.159 --> 00:13:58.320
When start-ups would make their product accessible via various ways, and then we can build a

00:13:58.320 --> 00:14:03.520
landing page with CNAME to make our Shiny app more accessible.

00:14:03.520 --> 00:14:07.599
Lastly, word of mouth can be a powerful marketing tool.

00:14:07.599 --> 00:14:12.359
And we can enable that by creating things like work results, work progress, and customized

00:14:12.359 --> 00:14:15.039
messages for the users to share.

00:14:16.039 --> 00:14:21.760
Now, after that, there's one more thing, operations.

00:14:21.760 --> 00:14:25.679
So like start-ups, Shiny apps is not something that's one and done.

00:14:25.679 --> 00:14:29.760
It is something that will require a continuous development.

00:14:29.760 --> 00:14:34.679
And for both start-ups and Shiny apps, the one thing that they need to take care of is

00:14:34.679 --> 00:14:35.919
customers.

00:14:35.919 --> 00:14:39.559
So while you can see that the start-ups, they will spend a lot of efforts to try to ensure

00:14:39.559 --> 00:14:44.919
there is a smooth customer onboarding experience, for Shiny apps, we need to make sure our

00:14:45.599 --> 00:14:52.039
apps are still user-friendly or providing a smooth experience for the new users by placing

00:14:52.039 --> 00:14:59.559
resources like a detailed readme or recording instructions.

00:14:59.559 --> 00:15:04.080
So while start-ups would also care about the customer success, we will need to think about

00:15:04.080 --> 00:15:09.799
if we are providing the ways to gather feedback to provide what the user needs.

00:15:09.799 --> 00:15:13.739
One of the other things that the start-ups will need to take care of are the communication

00:15:13.739 --> 00:15:16.460
with their investors.

00:15:16.460 --> 00:15:21.059
And if you think about all of these quarterly financial calls, almost every single one of

00:15:21.059 --> 00:15:26.099
them will follow the following structure that will start with a financial performance review

00:15:26.099 --> 00:15:27.099
for the last quarter.

00:15:27.099 --> 00:15:31.859
And they'll talk about any operational highlights or wins or challenges and end it with guidance

00:15:31.859 --> 00:15:32.859
or outlook.

00:15:32.859 --> 00:15:38.099
For Shiny apps, it is also very important for us to connect with our stakeholders to

00:15:38.099 --> 00:15:40.659
let them know what's going on with the investments.

00:15:40.659 --> 00:15:46.380
Similarly, we can follow the structure that starts with the app usage and impact.

00:15:46.380 --> 00:15:54.059
Then we talk about any wins or challenges along the way and end it with what to expect next.

00:15:54.059 --> 00:15:58.299
Overall, while start-ups will support the customer onboarding and success, we need to

00:15:58.299 --> 00:16:02.700
make sure we are engaging both new and existing users.

00:16:02.700 --> 00:16:08.700
When companies would do at least a quarterly financial call with investors, we need to

00:16:08.739 --> 00:16:13.419
make sure we're considering meeting regularly with the stakeholders to let them know that

00:16:13.419 --> 00:16:17.179
their investments are still healthy.

00:16:17.179 --> 00:16:21.619
Now you can probably see that building and launching a Shiny app is just like starting

00:16:21.619 --> 00:16:27.979
a company, where we will all start from an idea and then we need to validate the idea

00:16:27.979 --> 00:16:30.739
before any development.

00:16:30.739 --> 00:16:35.780
When we need resources, we need to reach out to the managers, stakeholders, or users for

00:16:35.780 --> 00:16:36.780
help.

00:16:36.859 --> 00:16:40.580
And when it comes to the product development or the app development, knowing that there

00:16:40.580 --> 00:16:45.820
are so many great resources out there, we still need to just try to keep only the necessary

00:16:45.820 --> 00:16:51.780
features and manage any new requests that come along the way.

00:16:51.780 --> 00:16:53.539
Building the app is not enough.

00:16:53.539 --> 00:16:58.700
We need to market the product by giving it a brand identity, starting with a name, make

00:16:58.700 --> 00:17:04.260
it more accessible with CNAME as well as a landing page, and create shareable information

00:17:04.260 --> 00:17:05.819
for the users.

00:17:05.859 --> 00:17:09.900
Lastly, Shiny app is not something that's one and done.

00:17:09.900 --> 00:17:13.099
It is something that will require a continuous effort.

00:17:13.099 --> 00:17:17.819
While we're making sure we're engaging with both new and existing users, let's make sure

00:17:17.819 --> 00:17:22.699
also plan out the connection with the stakeholders to talk about what's happened, what's new,

00:17:22.699 --> 00:17:24.099
and what's next.

00:17:24.099 --> 00:17:28.979
Overall, the whole journey is the Shiny app.

00:17:28.979 --> 00:17:35.020
Now if you forgot everything we just talked about or if you just walked in, remember this.

00:17:35.140 --> 00:17:38.939
Whenever you feel lost in a Shiny app journey, just think about what the startup direction

00:17:38.939 --> 00:17:41.699
would be, and you will be just fine.

00:17:41.699 --> 00:17:42.699
Thank you.

00:17:42.699 --> 00:17:43.699
All right.

00:17:43.699 --> 00:17:44.699
Thank you, Tiger.

